00:00:09.060 --> 00:00:14.589
The map idea is something
that arose because I write

00:00:14.589 --> 00:00:15.880
for The Guardian and I'm also--

00:00:15.880 --> 00:00:17.710
Obviously, I'm a teacher at UCL.

00:00:17.710 --> 00:00:21.790
And you get used to explaining
fairly abstruse details

00:00:21.790 --> 00:00:24.250
of physics to people.

00:00:24.250 --> 00:00:26.170
And if the audience
is paying attention

00:00:26.170 --> 00:00:28.000
and if you're doing
your job properly,

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:29.050
then it can kind of work.

00:00:29.050 --> 00:00:30.970
You can pretty much
explain anything.

00:00:30.970 --> 00:00:33.670
But then you realise that people
acquire a bit of knowledge here

00:00:33.670 --> 00:00:35.650
and a bit of knowledge there and
they've no real idea of the big

00:00:35.650 --> 00:00:38.260
picture, have these all
things linked together.

00:00:38.260 --> 00:00:42.490
So my idea of the map has sort
of come from how, in my head,

00:00:42.490 --> 00:00:44.340
I kind of view these things.

00:00:44.340 --> 00:00:45.940
The particle
physics, in general,

00:00:45.940 --> 00:00:48.520
and what we're trying to
do in particle physics

00:00:48.520 --> 00:00:51.380
in terms of the big picture of
how these things fit together.

00:00:51.380 --> 00:00:53.320
So I'm going to try and
talk you through that.

00:00:53.320 --> 00:00:54.320
You can think of it as--

00:00:54.320 --> 00:00:56.620
I also get asked how do you
picture the strange things

00:00:56.620 --> 00:00:57.860
that you study at CERN.

00:00:57.860 --> 00:01:00.490
Well this is, if you'd like, a
view of what goes on in my head

00:01:00.490 --> 00:01:01.344
sometimes.

00:01:01.344 --> 00:01:03.760
What we're going to do here--
it could be quite disturbing

00:01:03.760 --> 00:01:06.684
sometimes there.

00:01:06.684 --> 00:01:09.350
So I'm going to take you on some
journeys into particle physics.

00:01:09.350 --> 00:01:11.830
Now we don't have long enough
to go through the whole book.

00:01:11.830 --> 00:01:13.600
And I'm not going
to try, don't worry.

00:01:13.600 --> 00:01:14.950
So we'll skip over some bits.

00:01:14.950 --> 00:01:16.450
But we are going
to try and give you

00:01:16.450 --> 00:01:18.070
an idea of what our mission is.

00:01:18.070 --> 00:01:20.740
And what it's all
about is understanding

00:01:20.740 --> 00:01:22.630
the fundamental
constituents of matter.

00:01:22.630 --> 00:01:24.659
What is the physical
universe made of when

00:01:24.659 --> 00:01:25.700
you get right down to it?

00:01:25.700 --> 00:01:28.760
If you break things into
smaller and smaller pieces,

00:01:28.760 --> 00:01:31.380
do you end up with a common list
of the same pieces everything

00:01:31.380 --> 00:01:32.020
is made of?

00:01:32.020 --> 00:01:34.240
And what are the forces
between those things?

00:01:34.240 --> 00:01:36.700
And the answer at the
moment is, yes you do.

00:01:36.700 --> 00:01:41.710
You end up with a finite number
of infinitely small, what

00:01:41.710 --> 00:01:44.830
we call, fundamental objects
that everything else is

00:01:44.830 --> 00:01:45.400
made of.

00:01:45.400 --> 00:01:49.840
And the first of those objects
was discovered by this guy.

00:01:49.840 --> 00:01:54.580
This is JJ Thompson at Cambridge
with his experiment sitting

00:01:54.580 --> 00:01:55.400
on his desktop.

00:01:55.400 --> 00:01:58.360
And what he was doing was
studying a phenomenon,

00:01:58.360 --> 00:02:01.050
then was called cathode rays.

00:02:01.050 --> 00:02:03.480
This is his cathode ray tube.

00:02:03.480 --> 00:02:05.460
There's a gas in there
that's fluorescing

00:02:05.460 --> 00:02:08.320
as these mysterious
rays pass through it.

00:02:08.320 --> 00:02:11.860
And you create them by
heating up an electrode here

00:02:11.860 --> 00:02:13.630
and applying an
electromagnetic field.

00:02:13.630 --> 00:02:17.050
Which was all very cutting
edge stuff at the time.

00:02:17.050 --> 00:02:19.970
And he did various
experiments balancing

00:02:19.970 --> 00:02:21.730
electric and magnetic
forces and showed

00:02:21.730 --> 00:02:24.760
that these things were actually
corpuscules that always had

00:02:24.760 --> 00:02:26.234
the same master charge ratio.

00:02:26.234 --> 00:02:28.150
And then they devise
ways to measure the mass.

00:02:28.150 --> 00:02:29.740
And in the end it
convinced everyone

00:02:29.740 --> 00:02:31.750
that these were not waves,
they were particles,

00:02:31.750 --> 00:02:33.470
they were electrons, in fact.

00:02:33.470 --> 00:02:35.440
And that, the electron
than was established

00:02:35.440 --> 00:02:37.060
as the first
subatomic particle and

00:02:37.060 --> 00:02:39.040
the first fundamental particle.

00:02:39.040 --> 00:02:41.532
And despite 100
years of trying, it's

00:02:41.532 --> 00:02:42.740
still a fundamental particle.

00:02:42.740 --> 00:02:44.860
We have not managed to
break one of them yet.

00:02:44.860 --> 00:02:47.235
As far as we can see, there's
nothing inside an electron.

00:02:47.235 --> 00:02:48.970
It is infinitely small.

00:02:48.970 --> 00:02:52.030
And it is our sort of
gateway to this map.

00:02:52.030 --> 00:02:57.470
So this is us on a little boat
here coming in from the west.

00:02:57.470 --> 00:02:59.500
The west here is kind
of everyday life.

00:02:59.500 --> 00:03:02.777
And as we go further east
we get smaller and smaller

00:03:02.777 --> 00:03:04.360
and we go to higher
and higher energy.

00:03:04.360 --> 00:03:06.318
And I'll show you how
those things are actually

00:03:06.318 --> 00:03:08.010
the same thing shortly.

00:03:08.010 --> 00:03:14.510
But the electron is our port of
access to this subatomic world.

00:03:14.510 --> 00:03:17.170
And the first place you
kind of go from there

00:03:17.170 --> 00:03:20.080
is atomic physics.

00:03:20.080 --> 00:03:22.105
The electron is a
subatomic particle.

00:03:22.105 --> 00:03:24.360
There are electrons
in every atom.

00:03:24.360 --> 00:03:26.620
And you very quickly start--

00:03:26.620 --> 00:03:29.380
you're able to work out
that an atom is not--

00:03:29.380 --> 00:03:34.600
although an atom of say, sodium,
is the smallest piece of sodium

00:03:34.600 --> 00:03:35.687
you can possibly get.

00:03:35.687 --> 00:03:37.270
It's not the smallest
piece of matter.

00:03:37.270 --> 00:03:39.010
You can break a sodium atom up.

00:03:39.010 --> 00:03:42.897
You can break it into
electrons and a nucleus.

00:03:42.897 --> 00:03:44.230
And it won't be sodium any more.

00:03:44.230 --> 00:03:46.960
But there are still smaller
things inside the atom,

00:03:46.960 --> 00:03:48.920
in sodium.

00:03:48.920 --> 00:03:50.560
And the same for all atoms.

00:03:50.560 --> 00:03:54.420
So you start looking around
on the periodic table.

00:03:54.420 --> 00:04:00.347
And you find that life is a
little different in this map.

00:04:00.347 --> 00:04:02.680
We've travelled to something
that isn't actually looking

00:04:02.680 --> 00:04:05.002
quite like everyday life.

00:04:05.002 --> 00:04:06.460
And the first
manifestation of that

00:04:06.460 --> 00:04:10.820
is that when you have electrons
bound to these nuclei,

00:04:10.820 --> 00:04:13.240
you find that
they're not allowed

00:04:13.240 --> 00:04:14.620
to have just any old energy.

00:04:14.620 --> 00:04:17.140
They're bound in fixed orbits.

00:04:17.140 --> 00:04:21.339
Now orbits in the solar system,
which is the kind of model

00:04:21.339 --> 00:04:23.740
that Bohr had for the atom.

00:04:23.740 --> 00:04:25.630
Orbits in the solar
system, once you

00:04:25.630 --> 00:04:28.300
fix the distance of a
planet from the sun,

00:04:28.300 --> 00:04:30.800
than its velocity, is
period of orbit, is fixed.

00:04:30.800 --> 00:04:32.620
So there is a certain
lack of flexibility

00:04:32.620 --> 00:04:35.250
already there, for
a stable orbit.

00:04:35.250 --> 00:04:36.895
But with the atoms
it's even worse.

00:04:36.895 --> 00:04:38.770
There's only certain
orbits that are allowed.

00:04:38.770 --> 00:04:40.510
In principle, the
earth could have--

00:04:40.510 --> 00:04:42.674
it could be anywhere on
a continuum from the sun.

00:04:42.674 --> 00:04:44.590
It could be very hot or
it could be very cold.

00:04:44.590 --> 00:04:46.162
It can be anywhere in between.

00:04:46.162 --> 00:04:47.620
But that's not true
for an electron

00:04:47.620 --> 00:04:48.661
going around the nucleus.

00:04:48.661 --> 00:04:53.099
There's only certain energies
of orbit that it can have.

00:04:53.099 --> 00:04:54.640
And it turns out
that that's actually

00:04:54.640 --> 00:04:57.370
because the orbit model is
not a good model in the end.

00:04:57.370 --> 00:04:59.970
It's not a good picture
of what's going on.

00:04:59.970 --> 00:05:01.860
The best feature that's
going on is actually

00:05:01.860 --> 00:05:03.620
you have to take this
fundamental particle

00:05:03.620 --> 00:05:06.840
and you have to introduce
wavelike properties to it.

00:05:06.840 --> 00:05:10.140
Because the best analogy
that we think of here is you

00:05:10.140 --> 00:05:14.310
can imagine where in nature are
the discontinuous things where

00:05:14.310 --> 00:05:17.580
you can't have a contimum
of energies, for instance.

00:05:17.580 --> 00:05:21.750
And that happens with waves, it
happens on the guitar strings.

00:05:21.750 --> 00:05:24.890
So a guitar string will
support a fundamental note.

00:05:24.890 --> 00:05:26.850
It will support a
harmonic one octave up.

00:05:26.850 --> 00:05:28.469
It will support
the next harmonic.

00:05:28.469 --> 00:05:29.760
But that's all it will support.

00:05:29.760 --> 00:05:31.510
You can't have notes
in between unless you

00:05:31.510 --> 00:05:33.270
start pressing threats
down and changing

00:05:33.270 --> 00:05:35.290
the length of the strings.

00:05:35.290 --> 00:05:37.395
And that's the analogy
that Bohr initially used.

00:05:37.395 --> 00:05:38.770
And that's the
analogy that leads

00:05:38.770 --> 00:05:41.860
to quantum mechanics, in fact,
for how the electrons are

00:05:41.860 --> 00:05:43.930
bound around an atom.

00:05:43.930 --> 00:05:46.420
So it turns out the
electrons can only

00:05:46.420 --> 00:05:49.270
have these particular orbits
because that certain number

00:05:49.270 --> 00:05:52.450
of wavelengths of the electron
fit into that particular orbit.

00:05:52.450 --> 00:05:54.030
There are certain
barren states that

00:05:54.030 --> 00:05:56.150
have particular
resonant frequencies.

00:05:56.150 --> 00:05:57.952
And they're the only
ones that are allowed.

00:05:57.952 --> 00:05:59.410
And if you want to
change them, you

00:05:59.410 --> 00:06:00.826
have to change the
electric charge

00:06:00.826 --> 00:06:03.070
of the nucleus which
is like changing

00:06:03.070 --> 00:06:04.882
the length of the string.

00:06:04.882 --> 00:06:09.271
So that means that when the
electrons jump between orbits,

00:06:09.271 --> 00:06:11.020
and this is how we
knew this was the case,

00:06:11.020 --> 00:06:13.715
that they will emit energy
at certain frequencies,

00:06:13.715 --> 00:06:15.956
at certain energy levels.

00:06:15.956 --> 00:06:17.330
And that is, in
fact, how we know

00:06:17.330 --> 00:06:20.020
what anything that we
can't touch or smell

00:06:20.020 --> 00:06:20.900
is actually made of.

00:06:20.900 --> 00:06:24.750
So this is a spectrum,
electromagnetic spectrum,

00:06:24.750 --> 00:06:28.070
of a fluorescent bulb.

00:06:28.070 --> 00:06:30.652
You can see as you excite
the electrons in there,

00:06:30.652 --> 00:06:32.360
they're jumping between
particular levels

00:06:32.360 --> 00:06:34.026
and they give off
particular wavelengths

00:06:34.026 --> 00:06:36.690
of light corresponding
to those energy levels.

00:06:36.690 --> 00:06:39.620
And likewise, this is a
spectrum, this is from the sun.

00:06:39.620 --> 00:06:41.686
This is the emission
spectrum of the sun.

00:06:41.686 --> 00:06:43.310
And you see there
are dark lines in it.

00:06:43.310 --> 00:06:44.768
And each one of
these dark lines is

00:06:44.768 --> 00:06:47.260
where elements in
the sun's atmosphere

00:06:47.260 --> 00:06:49.100
are absorbing
particular energies

00:06:49.100 --> 00:06:50.870
because those energies,
the electrons,

00:06:50.870 --> 00:06:52.550
can jump between levels.

00:06:52.550 --> 00:06:55.490
And these characterise the
elements there in the sun.

00:06:55.490 --> 00:06:57.800
So the only reason
that we know what

00:06:57.800 --> 00:07:00.860
the stars and the planets
that are not our own planet

00:07:00.860 --> 00:07:04.390
are made of, is by observing
these kind of emission spectra.

00:07:04.390 --> 00:07:06.555
In fact, the element helium
was just called helium

00:07:06.555 --> 00:07:07.900
from Heliox, the sun god.

00:07:07.900 --> 00:07:10.280
It was discovered on the
sun before we discovered it

00:07:10.280 --> 00:07:13.820
on the earth by looking
at emission lines.

00:07:13.820 --> 00:07:16.550
So that introduces, although
the electron started off

00:07:16.550 --> 00:07:18.830
as a fundamental
particle, it's now

00:07:18.830 --> 00:07:21.050
suddenly got wavelike
properties because it's

00:07:21.050 --> 00:07:22.970
like a note on a guitar string.

00:07:22.970 --> 00:07:27.410
And that's the kind of, the
insight in quantum mechanics,

00:07:27.410 --> 00:07:29.945
actually these fundamental
particles are not particles.

00:07:29.945 --> 00:07:31.560
Neither are the ruby waves.

00:07:31.560 --> 00:07:34.520
They're a new kind of object
called a quantum excitation,

00:07:34.520 --> 00:07:36.120
if you like.

00:07:36.120 --> 00:07:38.640
But because of those
wavelike properties,

00:07:38.640 --> 00:07:41.630
there's then the very clear
connection between the energy

00:07:41.630 --> 00:07:42.740
and the size.

00:07:42.740 --> 00:07:47.727
So on this map, as we
go east, we're going--

00:07:47.727 --> 00:07:49.310
looking at smaller
and smaller things,

00:07:49.310 --> 00:07:50.643
deeper into the heart of matter.

00:07:50.643 --> 00:07:52.550
But we're also
going up in energy.

00:07:52.550 --> 00:07:55.460
And the best way of illustrating
that connection here

00:07:55.460 --> 00:07:57.330
is in this little
video that I've got,

00:07:57.330 --> 00:07:59.840
which I hope I can make work.

00:07:59.840 --> 00:08:00.874
This is super high tech.

00:08:00.874 --> 00:08:02.290
You're going to
see a ripple tank.

00:08:05.320 --> 00:08:07.750
But I think it really
shows you what's going on.

00:08:07.750 --> 00:08:09.970
And this is this connection
between the very small

00:08:09.970 --> 00:08:11.360
and the very large.

00:08:11.360 --> 00:08:13.690
So if you imagine this as a
beam of particles, and this

00:08:13.690 --> 00:08:14.920
is my detector here.

00:08:14.920 --> 00:08:17.950
OK, and I'm looking
for some new particle.

00:08:17.950 --> 00:08:21.960
So someone is going to put
a blob in there in a moment.

00:08:21.960 --> 00:08:24.070
Come on with the blob.

00:08:24.070 --> 00:08:26.700
They always take longer than
I think they're going to.

00:08:26.700 --> 00:08:27.440
So they put a blob in there.

00:08:27.440 --> 00:08:29.814
You guys see how a particle
detector will have spotted it

00:08:29.814 --> 00:08:31.530
because this is a shadow.

00:08:31.530 --> 00:08:33.305
So you could register
this presence.

00:08:33.305 --> 00:08:34.679
If you did some
calculations, you

00:08:34.679 --> 00:08:37.770
could probably tell what
size it was, maybe even what

00:08:37.770 --> 00:08:40.393
shape it was if you were very
careful with your measurements.

00:08:40.393 --> 00:08:41.684
So that works as an experiment.

00:08:41.684 --> 00:08:43.919
Now they put another blob in.

00:08:43.919 --> 00:08:45.940
This blob now is
completely invisible.

00:08:45.940 --> 00:08:47.610
If you look, the
detecter can't see it

00:08:47.610 --> 00:08:49.604
because the waves
reform around it.

00:08:49.604 --> 00:08:52.020
And that's because the blob
is smaller than the wavelength

00:08:52.020 --> 00:08:52.731
of the waves.

00:08:52.731 --> 00:08:54.480
So we don't have the
resolution to see it.

00:08:54.480 --> 00:08:56.370
So what do we do, we
turn up the energy,

00:08:56.370 --> 00:08:58.720
which turns up the frequency,
shortens the wavelength.

00:08:58.720 --> 00:09:01.200
And now you see the
shadow forming again,

00:09:01.200 --> 00:09:04.050
you can see it again.

00:09:04.050 --> 00:09:05.560
So that's really
this connection.

00:09:05.560 --> 00:09:07.143
That's what particle
physics is about.

00:09:07.143 --> 00:09:10.080
That's why we have
high energy machines.

00:09:10.080 --> 00:09:13.050
Because we want to
see small stuff.

00:09:13.050 --> 00:09:16.580
If we want to see small stuff,
we need short wavelengths.

00:09:16.580 --> 00:09:19.489
If we want short
wavelengths we need to see--

00:09:19.489 --> 00:09:21.030
We need to-- sorry,
I've just spotted

00:09:21.030 --> 00:09:21.845
an old friend in the audience.

00:09:21.845 --> 00:09:22.590
It put me off.

00:09:22.590 --> 00:09:23.786
Hi, Nigel!

00:09:27.050 --> 00:09:30.285
If you want to see small things,
you need short wavelengths.

00:09:30.285 --> 00:09:33.750
So that means high frequency,
which means high energy.

00:09:33.750 --> 00:09:39.720
So that's why particle physics
is also high energy physics.

00:09:39.720 --> 00:09:42.240
That's why we need huge
colliders and things to try

00:09:42.240 --> 00:09:45.420
and see the very small stuff,
because of this connection

00:09:45.420 --> 00:09:48.630
between wavelength,
frequency and resolution.

00:09:48.630 --> 00:09:51.047
If you think about it, if our
eyes are sensitive to radar,

00:09:51.047 --> 00:09:52.629
then I wouldn't be
able to see you now

00:09:52.629 --> 00:09:54.390
because radar has
wavelengths of metres

00:09:54.390 --> 00:09:55.681
and you'd be smaller than that.

00:09:55.681 --> 00:09:56.602
So I wouldn't see you.

00:09:56.602 --> 00:09:58.560
But our eyes are actually
sensitive to hundreds

00:09:58.560 --> 00:10:01.866
of nanometers, which is pretty
good for seeing small stuff.

00:10:01.866 --> 00:10:03.240
But if you wanted
to see smaller,

00:10:03.240 --> 00:10:05.820
you'd go up in energy, which
means x-rays, or electron

00:10:05.820 --> 00:10:07.230
microscopes, and in it.

00:10:07.230 --> 00:10:08.730
So you can think
of the big particle

00:10:08.730 --> 00:10:10.438
colliders like the
Large Hadron Collider,

00:10:10.438 --> 00:10:12.000
is just the biggest,
most powerful,

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:15.532
highest resolution
microscopes we can build.

00:10:15.532 --> 00:10:17.990
So I've already mentioned the
Large Hadron Collider, that's

00:10:17.990 --> 00:10:19.970
one of the stars of the show.

00:10:19.970 --> 00:10:22.020
At least you get to
the east of the map.

00:10:22.020 --> 00:10:24.380
So I'm kind of
skipping over a whole

00:10:24.380 --> 00:10:26.370
of the rest of this
stuff, which is

00:10:26.370 --> 00:10:32.080
there is kind of our exploration
of the subatomic world.

00:10:32.080 --> 00:10:35.420
And bringing you right
up to date to what's

00:10:35.420 --> 00:10:36.515
going on the east coast.

00:10:36.515 --> 00:10:38.660
So this, this is
if you like, this

00:10:38.660 --> 00:10:40.952
is the standard model on
the threshold of ruining

00:10:40.952 --> 00:10:42.035
the Large Hadron Collider.

00:10:42.035 --> 00:10:44.810
Now that's my, the weird
stuff that goes on in my head,

00:10:44.810 --> 00:10:45.310
if you like.

00:10:45.310 --> 00:10:49.380
This is a more conventional way
of viewing the standard model.

00:10:49.380 --> 00:10:55.420
It tells us that we
have the electron here,

00:10:55.420 --> 00:10:56.760
our old friend that we saw.

00:10:56.760 --> 00:10:58.460
It's been around
for a long time.

